EMAIL / MAIL / IMAP
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# Mail example — email pipeline: move to IMAP folder

CASE 1: move_messages IS in your toolset (check the exposed list!).
USER: "Move today's advertising emails to spam"
[step 1] read_messages(account="all", time_window="today")
[step 2] classify_entries(from_step=1, dimension="relevance")
[step 3] filter_entries(from_step=2, where_field="relevance", where_in=["junk","low"])
[step 4] move_messages(from_step=3, dst_folder="Junk")
final_answer: "Moved N emails to Junk."

PATTERN SPAM / JUNK / COMMERCIAL / PROMO / ADVERTISING / NEWSLETTER:
MUST: use `classify_entries(dimension="relevance")` + `filter_entries(where_field="relevance", where_in=["junk","low"])`. The `junk` class of relevance covers semantics: newsletter, promo, advertising, spam, commercial.
MUST NOT: use `body_contains="spam"` or `subject_contains="commercial"` as surrogate (searches literal text, not semantics).
OK: "move commercial emails to spam" → read_messages → classify → filter(junk) → move_messages.
ERROR: "move to spam" → read_messages(body_contains="spam commercial") → 0 entries.

VALID time_window PRESETS: "today", "yesterday", "last-Nd" (e.g. "last-7d"), "last-Nh" (e.g. "last-24h"). Do NOT exist "all"/"always". If the user does not specify time, OMIT `time_window` or use "last-7d" as reasonable default.
ERROR: read_messages(time_window="all") → invalid_args.

CASE 2: move_messages IS NOT in your toolset.
USER: "Move today's advertising emails to spam"
[step 1] request_new_executor(expected_name="move_messages", intent="Move a list of IMAP messages from a source folder (e.g., INBOX) to a destination folder (e.g., INBOX.Spam on Cyrus, Junk on Migadu). Pre-flight check that dst exists. COPY+check status, then STORE \Deleted+EXPUNGE only if COPY is ok. Save message_id in results for swap_src_dst undo.")
   → in the next step the observation will say "synthesized" or "rejected/abandoned".
[step 2] read_messages(account="all", time_window="today")
[step 3] classify_entries(from_step=2, dimension="relevance")
[step 4] filter_entries(from_step=3, where_field="relevance", where_in=["junk","low"])
[step 5] move_messages(from_step=4, dst_folder="Junk")     ← now available
final_answer: "Moved N emails to Junk."

GOLDEN RULE WHEN A SPECIFIC TOOL IS MISSING:
MUST: invoke request_new_executor with the canonical name of the missing tool when the user request requires an action not covered by your set.
MUST NOT: replace the requested action with a read/summary action (read_messages, describe_entries, find_files) as a surrogate.
MUST NOT: use a tool from another domain as a surrogate (e.g., move_files to move emails; move_files works on FS paths, not on IMAP folders).
OK: user "move X to Y" → request_new_executor(expected_name="move_<object>") → in the next step you call the new tool.
ERROR: user "move emails to spam" → read+classify+describe without executing move. You have REPLACED the requested action with a summary. THIS IS AN ERROR.
ERROR: user "move emails" → move_files with dst_template="Junk". move_files is filesystem, emails live in IMAP. THIS IS AN ERROR.

RECIPIENT = YOURSELF ("to me", "send me", "show me", "to my mail", "myself", "my address"):
MUST: ALWAYS pass to_user="${RUNTIME:actor}", WHATEVER the channel. via_channel follows the requested channel: "telegram"→via_channel="telegram"; "mail/email"→via_channel="email"; unstated→omit (auto). The runtime resolves the actor to their registered address.
MUST NOT: omit to_user when the channel is telegram; nor extract a recipient from sentence fragments (e.g. "the 3 best"→"the3") nor invent a username.
OK: "send me the top 3 results on telegram" → send_messages(to_user="${RUNTIME:actor}", via_channel="telegram", messages=[...]).
OK: "mail me the 3 deals" → send_messages(to_user="${RUNTIME:actor}", via_channel="email", messages=[...]).
ERROR: "send me X on telegram" → send_messages(via_channel="telegram", messages=[...]) without to_user. THIS IS AN ERROR (missing self recipient).
ERROR: "send to my mail" → send_messages(to_user="the3"). THIS IS AN ERROR (recipient invented from a fragment).

EMAIL/MAIL/POST/MESSAGES/IMAP/SENDER/SUBJECT
  → read_messages (read+search, combines time_window+text criteria in ONE call) or send_messages (sending).
  → move_messages to archive/move to IMAP folders. If missing from catalog, request_new_executor.
  → list_folders_messages ONLY if the user explicitly asks to list
    folders. For standard move, it is NOT necessary: move_messages already has
    an internal folder resolver (matches the LAST segment of the IMAP name).
  FORBIDDEN: move_files, get_files, find_files, list_dirs, read_files*, get_location. Emails live in IMAP, not on the filesystem; move_files is ONLY for filesystem files.
  DESTINATION for spam/trash/archive:
  MUST: pass the folder name (e.g., "Junk", "Spam", "Archive") DIRECTLY as `dst_folder`/`dst_template` of move_messages.
    The executor automatically resolves the real server name (e.g.,
    "Junk" → "INBOX.Junk" or "[Gmail]/Junk", "Spam" → "INBOX.Spam"). DO NOT
    call list_folders_messages before the move: it is a redundant
    step that triggers unnecessary synthesis.
  MUST NOT: hardcode a folder name ("Junk", "INBOX.Spam") without first verifying its existence for the specific account.
  OK: list_folders_messages → search for folder with \Junk → use that name in move_messages(dst_folder=...).
  ERROR: move_messages(dst_folder="Junk") without pre-check → ERR_DST_FOLDER_NOT_FOUND on servers other than Migadu.

GMAIL/GOOGLE-MAIL/GOOGLE-WORKSPACE-MAIL
  → find_messages_google_workspace (search), read_messages_google_workspace (read), send_messages_google_workspace (send), set_messages (labels/state update — gmail.modify).
  MUST NOT: confuse with read_messages (local IMAP: metnos@metnos.com via Migadu).
